 Under **GDPR Article 32(1)**, a controller (and processor) must take into account the following specific factors when determining what constitutes 'appropriate' technical and organisational security measures:

1. **The state of the art** — current technological developments and industry standards available at the time;
2. **The costs of implementation** — the expense associated with putting the security measures in place;
3. **The nature of the processing** — what kind of processing activities are being carried out;
4. **The scope of the processing** — the breadth or extent of the data processing;
5. **The context of the processing** — the circumstances surrounding the processing, including any relevant external factors;
6. **The purposes of the processing** — why the personal data is being processed; and
7. **The risk of varying likelihood and severity for the rights and freedoms of natural persons** — the potential risks posed by the processing to individuals.

**Source:** GDPR Article 32(1) — *"Taking into account the state of the art, the costs of implementation and the nature, scope, context and purposes of processing as well as the risk of varying likelihood and severity for the rights and freedoms of natural persons, the controller and the processor shall implement appropriate technical and organisational measures to ensure a level of security appropriate to the risk..."* (see [gdpr-info.eu/art-32-gdpr](https://gdpr-info.eu/art-32-gdpr) and [legislation.gov.uk/eur/2016/679/article/32](https://www.legislation.gov.uk/eur/2016/679/article/32)).

These factors must be weighed together to ensure the implemented measures provide a **level of security appropriate to the risk**. Article 32(1) then provides a non-exhaustive list of example measures (such as pseudonymisation, encryption, ensuring confidentiality/integrity/availability/resilience, restoring availability after incidents, and regularly testing measures).
